title: For Sale:  Tired of deadbeats asking for your "bottom dollar"?
location: Clearly not a classroom., St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Putting on an aftermarket stock does not make your SKS a custom rifle.
Putting new grips on your 1911 does not make your 1911 a custom piece.
Adding a bunch of 'tactical tupperware" does not make your $1,000 AR an $2,500 dollar rifle.
AR Mags are available and reasonable again, there are $16-$18 P-Mags all over town.
If you overpaid for something during the panic, don't expect it to have the same value now.  Looking at you WASR-10!
If someone says "No Taurus or Jennings or Bryco or Hi-Point guns" in their ad, that probably means they aren't looking for one, so don't offer that shit.
If someone says "No Trades" in their ad, do you think they might mean it?
If someone says "Not for sale" in their ad, do you think they weren't talking to you?
If someone says "Make offer", that means to make an offer.  If you ask them for their bottom dollar, they should ask you for your top dollar.  Man up and make an offer!
If you're expecting MSRP value for your gun, then accept the MSRP value of the other guy's.
If you've got something in your picture that doesn't come with the gun like a scope or ammo or holster, take it out of the picture!


READ THE DAMNED ADS BEFORE RESPONDING, AND YOU WILL AVIOID LOOKING LIKE A JACKASS.

title: For Sale:  Walther P5 (COMPACT) RARE FIND
postcontent: If your looking for an Ideal carry 9mm that no one else owns, then the Walther P5 compact is the weapon for you. It's the 9mm big brother to Walther's PPK. It's even been used in several films with Sean Connery and Roger Moore and the Bourne series . No longer made, the P5 was brought into the US in the 80's. This one was from 1986. It's the perfect size for carry but remains extremely accurate. It packs a powerful punch a 9 x 19 full size 9mm should. It has some great German features that put the battery release to use as a decocker. It ejects to left. The magazine release has been brought up on the grip in the P5 compact. the magazines spring out promptly as they should.  That is the hard to find version.  I like that better than it's predessors and other European pistols with the release on the heel. This is truly a rare gun.  Don't confuse it with the P5, it's a fine gun but not as rare as the P5 COMPACT like this one.  It has the coolness of a ppk, but it's a full 9mm. It comes with the hard to find custom holster, the original box and manual and 2-7 round clips.  I just got this pistol back from the gun smith. now it's even more rare. I had him put a nickel finish on it for me. It looks awesome.  It's only been fired by the gun smith after reassembly to verify operation. It's in immaculate condition. title: For Sale:  SASS, Cowboy Action Shooting Gun Cart
postcontent:
By CalGraf Designs, for sale is a coffin gun cart.  This cart was bought and stored, but never actually used.  Very well made cart.  The details from CalGraf is below:





At last!  An actual "covered" cart—sit on it, play cards, clean your guns on the Cowboy Coffin Cart . . .





The Cowboy Coffin is the secure way to keep your weapons from dust, dirt and the bad guys.  It holds 5 long guns (3 rifles, 2 shotguns) in the same sort of cradle as the Range Kart.  But, instead of a Range Box or other sort of box, there is a compartment for your cartridges and handguns in the lid of the Coffin, 16" x 16" x 4" with drop down lid that becomes a table.  Lid is held in place by slide hook on side.


Wheels are 16" hard rubber 1890s bicycle wheel spoked on a hardwood and steel axle that is tapped to accept the 1/2" threads on the wheels, and two 1/4" bolts secure it to the Coffin.


A 36 inch piano hinge is on the right side; the Coffin is approximately 47 1/2" inside height, and 20" wide at the "shoulders", inside measurement.  It is made of 3/4" pine, double-sided 1/2" birch plywood top and bottom with the side 3/4" pine.  The Coffin lid is held open by use of a dowel brace.  There is a leg on the top back as well as the leg corresponding to wheels underneath which work great for "hand-trucking" the Coffin around.  Easily removed without tools leaving only a Coffin with sisal rope handles. Between stages you can "lay it out" and sit on it!


Guns are able to be carried with the actions open, and you can remove your guns, muzzle up for safety and in compliance with the rules (or in the horizontal position as well).  As with our Original Range Kart, the Cowboy Gun Coffin can be disassembled—wheels, axle, legs.  The chain shown in several of the images has been replaced with a leather strap, also shown.


Cowboy Coffin weighs in at about 65#.   It is finished with a Watco oil.  Coffin pivots on wheels in upright position, held in place by base which provides stability.



FTF meeting in the Golden area. 
Shipping for this cart is running about $90 dur to the size and weight.  Prefer local pickup.
